```rust
impl Reactor for EpollReactor {
    fn poll(
        &self,
        events: &mut Events,
        timeout: Option<Duration>,
    ) -> io::Result<usize> {
        events.clear();

        // Convert timeout to milliseconds (-1 for infinite)
        let timeout_ms = timeout
            .map(|d| {
                // Clamp to i32::MAX to avoid overflow
                d.as_millis().min(i32::MAX as u128) as i32
            })
            .unwrap_or(-1);

        // Pre-allocate epoll events buffer
        let mut epoll_events = [EpollEvent::empty(); 256];

        // Wait for events
        let n = match epoll_wait(self.epoll_fd, &mut epoll_events, timeout_ms) {
            Ok(n) => n,
            Err(nix::errno::Errno::EINTR) => {
                // Interrupted by signal, return 0 events (caller will retry)
                return Ok(0);
            }
            Err(e) => {
                return Err(io::Error::from_raw_os_error(e as i32));
            }
        };

        // Collect wakers to wake AFTER releasing the lock
        let mut wakers_to_wake = Vec::with_capacity(n);

        {
            let inner = self.inner.lock().unwrap();

            // Process events
            for epoll_event in &epoll_events[..n] {
                let token = Token::from_usize(epoll_event.data() as usize);

                // Check if this is the wake_fd
                if self.is_wake_token(token) {
                    self.drain_wake_fd();
                    continue;
                }

                // Convert epoll flags to Interest
                let ready = self.epoll_flags_to_interest(epoll_event.events());
                events.push(Event { token, ready });

                // **CRITICAL: Collect waker for this token**
                if let Some(waker) = inner.wakers.get(token) {
                    wakers_to_wake.push(waker.clone());
                }
            }
        }

        // **CRITICAL: Wake all collected wakers OUTSIDE the lock**
        // This allows tasks to be scheduled without holding reactor lock
        for waker in wakers_to_wake {
            waker.wake();
        }

        Ok(events.len())
    }

    fn epoll_flags_to_interest(&self, flags: EpollFlags) -> Interest {
        let mut interest = Interest::empty();
        if flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLIN) {
            interest |= Interest::READABLE;
        }
        if flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLOUT) {
            interest |= Interest::WRITABLE;
        }
        if flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLPRI) {
            interest |= Interest::PRIORITY;
        }
        if flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLERR) {
            interest |= Interest::ERROR;
        }
        if flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLHUP) || flags.contains(EpollFlags::EPOLLRDHUP) {
            interest |= Interest::HUP;
        }
        interest
    }
}
```

## CRITICAL: Waker Dispatch

The **most important** part of poll() is waking the registered wakers:

1. For each event, look up the waker in `inner.wakers`
2. Clone the waker (to avoid holding lock while waking)
3. Call `waker.wake()` AFTER releasing the lock

Without this, futures waiting for I/O will **never be woken**\!

## Handling EINTR

`epoll_wait()` can return `EINTR` if a signal is received. We:
1. Don't treat this as an error
2. Return 0 events (caller will retry)

**NOTE**: Previous version had buggy `??` error handling. This is fixed above.

## Wake fd Processing

When wake_fd is ready:
1. Read to drain the eventfd counter
2. Don't include in returned events
3. Don't wake any waker (internal mechanism)
4. This just causes poll() to return so scheduler can run

```rust
fn drain_wake_fd(&self) {
    let mut buf = [0u8; 8];
    loop {
        match nix::unistd::read(self.wake_fd, &mut buf) {
            Ok(_) => continue,
            Err(nix::errno::Errno::EAGAIN) => break,
            Err(_) => break, // Ignore other errors
        }
    }
}
```

## Edge-Triggered Consideration

With EPOLLET, waker is woken once per readiness change. The future must:
1. Read/write until WouldBlock
2. Then return Pending (waker registered for next change)

If only partial read, caller needs to continue polling.

